==English==
===Etymology===
Outgrowth of the earlier idiom, to {{term|hit the sack}}, with possible influences from other senses of ''[[sack#Verb|to sack]]'' (tackle, pillage), and ''[[sock#Verb|to sock]]'' (hit, slam), providing an implication that sleep has been thrust upon a person.

===Verb===
{{en-verb|inf=to [[sack]] [[out]]|sacks out|sacking out|sacked out}}

# {{idiom}} To [[fall asleep]], usually from implied [[exhaustion]].
#: ''The kids '''sacked out''' in the back seat before we made it home.''

